<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<!--
  Screener prompt — EXAMPLE / template. Copy to screener.xml (gitignored) and write
  the real prompt there; the loader fails loud if screener.xml is absent (no fallback
  to this file). The instructions below are a deliberately generic skeleton — your
  real prompt carries the detailed rubric, guardrails, and output contract.

  Three sections are REQUIRED. They map to the message layout, which is split for
  prompt caching — the profile is large and stable, the posting small and volatile:
    - instructions    → system block 1: stable rules; cached with the profile.
    - profile_wrapper → system block 2: the candidate (cached prefix — reused across
                        every posting scored against the same profile).
    - user_template   → user turn: the per-posting payload (NOT cached).

  Placeholders use Python str.format — escape any literal brace as {{ }}.
  Interpolated from code (do not hardcode the numbers): {axis_weights},
  {apply_threshold}, {maybe_threshold}. Substituted at render: {profile},
  {ledger} (resolved skill ledger), {posting}, {preferences}, {baseline}
  (the deterministic verdict that escalated this posting).
-->
<prompt>
    <instructions><![CDATA[
You score how well a candidate fits a job posting. Return an `apply` / `maybe` / `skip`
verdict with a 0–100 match_score and short reasoning.

Weigh these axes (weights injected so the prompt can't drift from the scorer):
{axis_weights}

Decision bands:
  — match_score >= {apply_threshold} → "apply"
  — {maybe_threshold} <= match_score < {apply_threshold} → "maybe"
  — match_score < {maybe_threshold} → "skip"
    ]]></instructions>

    <!-- The candidate side: freeform body + the structured skill ledger the
         technical axis scores against. This whole block is the cached prefix. -->
    <profile_wrapper><![CDATA[
      <profile>{profile}</profile>
      <skill_ledger>
{ledger}
      </skill_ledger>
    ]]></profile_wrapper>

    <!-- The posting side + the deterministic baseline to refine or overturn. -->
    <user_template><![CDATA[
      <posting>{posting}</posting>
      <preferences>{preferences}</preferences>
      <baseline_verdict>{baseline}</baseline_verdict>
      The baseline_verdict is the deterministic arithmetic score. Refine or
      overturn it — return your own verdict for this posting.
    ]]></user_template>
</prompt>
